    relatedTextRefs: ["John 1:1", "Romans 3:23", "Philippians 2:5-11"],
    layers: {
      accessible:
        "Every book of the New Testament was written in Koine Greek -- 'koine' meaning 'common.' This was not the elegant literary Greek of Plato and Homer but the everyday language spoken across the Roman Empire after Alexander the Great spread Greek culture. Think of it as the difference between Shakespeare's English and a modern newspaper. This matters because the New Testament authors were not writing high literature (with a few exceptions like Hebrews). Paul's letters sound like passionate, sometimes rambling letters from someone who thinks faster than he writes. Mark's Gospel uses 'and immediately' over 40 times -- it reads like an excited oral storytelling. When translations make the Bible sound formal and elevated, they are adding a register the original did not have.",
      intermediate:
        "Greek has features that create theological precision impossible in English. The definite article: John 1:1 says 'the Word was with THE God (ton theon), and the Word was God (theos, no article).' This distinction is why scholars debate whether John means 'the Word was God' (identity) or 'the Word was divine' (quality). The article makes a theological difference.\n\nGreek verb tenses encode aspect, not just time. The aorist tense presents an action as a single complete event. The present tense presents it as ongoing. When Paul says 'all have sinned' (Romans 3:23), the aorist 'hemarton' treats sin as a completed fact of the human condition. When John says 'the one who practices sin' (1 John 3:9), the present participle implies ongoing, habitual action. This distinction matters for whether individual sins or a life orientation is meant.\n\nThe word 'agape' (love) is often claimed to be a uniquely Christian invention for divine love. This is a myth. Agape appears in secular Greek before Christianity. What the New Testament authors did was fill an existing word with new theological content -- particularly the idea that divine love is self-giving and directed toward the undeserving.",
      advanced:
        "The Greek text of the New Testament exists in roughly 5,800 manuscripts, no two of which are identical. Textual criticism -- the discipline of reconstructing the most likely original text -- is one of the most rigorous fields in biblical scholarship. The major critical editions (Nestle-Aland, now in its 28th edition, and the United Bible Societies text, 5th edition) represent scholarly consensus but involve thousands of judgment calls.\n\nSignificant textual variants: The ending of Mark (16:9-20) is almost certainly a later addition -- the earliest manuscripts end abruptly at 16:8 with the women fleeing the tomb in fear. The Pericope Adulterae (John 7:53-8:11, the woman caught in adultery) does not appear in the earliest manuscripts and floats to different locations in various manuscripts. The Comma Johanneum (1 John 5:7-8, the only explicit Trinitarian formula) is a medieval Latin addition absent from all Greek manuscripts before the 16th century.\n\nParticiples in Greek carry enormous theological weight. Philippians 2:6 -- 'who, being (hyparchon, present participle) in the form of God, did not consider equality with God something to be grasped (harpagmon).' The participial construction 'being in the form' implies continuous state, not a past condition. And 'harpagmon' is a hapax legomenon (appears only once in the NT), making its precise meaning debated: does it mean Christ did not grasp at equality he did not have, or did not cling to equality he already possessed? The entire Christological framework shifts depending on which reading you adopt."
    },
