    domainId: "d11",
    name: "Genre Recognition in Biblical Literature",
    summary:
      "The Bible contains poetry, law, narrative, prophecy, apocalyptic, parable, epistle, and wisdom -- each with its own rules. Reading poetry as law or apocalyptic as prediction creates bad theology.",
    lensTags: ["academic", "protestant", "catholic"],
    relatedConceptSlugs: ["hermeneutical-frameworks", "wisdom-literature"],
    relatedTextRefs: ["Revelation 1:1", "Psalm 137:9", "Genesis 1"],
    layers: {
      accessible:
        "The biggest interpretive mistake people make with the Bible is treating every passage the same way. The Bible is not a single book but a library of 66 books (or 73, or 81, depending on your tradition) spanning over a thousand years, written in multiple genres. Reading a psalm the same way you read a law code, or reading Revelation the same way you read a letter from Paul, will produce terrible interpretations. Psalm 137:9 says 'Happy is the one who seizes your infants and dashes them against the rocks.' If you read this as a command, it is horrifying. If you recognize it as a raw lament from a traumatized exile -- a cry of pain, not a prescription -- it becomes one of the most honest prayers in Scripture. Genre is not a technicality. It determines meaning.",
      intermediate:
        "Major biblical genres and their reading rules:\n\nNarrative (Genesis, Samuel, Kings, Acts): tells what happened but does not always endorse what characters do. When David commits adultery and murder, the text narrates it; it does not approve it. Narrative morality is complex.\n\nLaw (Exodus 20-23, Leviticus, Deuteronomy): embedded in narrative context. Laws were given for specific communities in specific circumstances. Some are universal principles (do not murder), some are case law for an agrarian society (what to do if your ox gores someone), and some are purity regulations for the Temple system that no longer exists. Sorting these categories requires theological judgment.\n\nProphecy (Isaiah, Jeremiah, Amos): primarily forth-telling (speaking God's message to the present), not fore-telling (predicting the future). Prophets addressed specific political and social crises. Reading them as coded predictions of events 2,500 years later (common in popular prophecy books) ignores their actual message.\n\nApocalyptic (Daniel 7-12, Revelation): uses symbolic, visionary imagery to address present suffering with cosmic hope. The 'beast' in Revelation is not a prediction of a future world leader but an encoded critique of Roman imperial power. Reading apocalyptic as a literal timeline of future events is a genre mistake.\n\nWisdom (Proverbs, Ecclesiastes, Job): general observations about how life usually works, not absolute promises. 'Train up a child in the way he should go, and when he is old he will not depart from it' (Proverbs 22:6) is a wise observation, not a divine guarantee. Ecclesiastes deliberately contradicts Proverbs -- the Bible contains internal debate.",
      advanced:
        "Genre theory in biblical studies has been significantly advanced by the work of John Collins (defining apocalyptic genre), Tremper Longman III (wisdom literature), and Robert Alter (narrative art). Alter's 'The Art of Biblical Narrative' demonstrated that biblical prose is not naive or primitive but uses sophisticated literary techniques: type-scenes (recurring patterns like the 'meeting at a well'), key-word repetition (Leitwort), and deliberate ambiguity.\n\nThe most significant genre debate currently concerns Genesis 1-11. Is it history, myth, theology, or something else? The options: (1) literal history (young earth creationism), (2) 'myth' in the scholarly sense (a true story about the human condition expressed in non-historical form), (3) polemic (an anti-Babylonian creation story -- 'our God created differently from Marduk'), (4) liturgy (Genesis 1 structured as a seven-day Temple inauguration). These are not mutually exclusive -- a text can function in multiple generic modes simultaneously.\n\nThe parables of Jesus represent a distinctive genre that has been consistently misread. Adolf Julicher (1888) established that parables are not allegories (where every detail symbolizes something) but comparisons that make one central point. Yet Mark 4:10-12 has Jesus say he teaches in parables so that outsiders will NOT understand -- which contradicts the idea that parables clarify. C.H. Dodd and Joachim Jeremias demonstrated that parables originally addressed specific situations in Jesus' ministry and were later allegorized by the early church (compare Mark's version of the Sower parable with its allegorical interpretation). The most productive recent approach (Amy-Jill Levine, 'Short Stories by Jesus') reads parables as provocations that challenge every audience, not as comfortable morality tales."
    },
