      accessible:
        "Jesus took bread, said 'this is my body,' took wine, said 'this is my blood,' and told his followers to keep doing this in remembrance of him. Every Christian tradition practices some form of communion. But they disagree about what happens. Catholics teach transubstantiation: the bread and wine literally become Christ's body and blood while keeping the appearance of bread and wine. Orthodox affirm a real change but refuse to define the mechanism (it is a 'mystery'). Lutherans teach that Christ is truly present 'in, with, and under' the bread and wine. Calvinists say Christ is spiritually (but really) present. Many evangelicals and Baptists treat it as purely symbolic -- a memorial meal.",
      intermediate:
        "The word 'transubstantiation' was formally defined at the Fourth Lateran Council (1215) using Aristotelian philosophy: the 'substance' (what a thing truly is) changes while the 'accidents' (what it looks like, tastes like) remain. This philosophical framework was cutting-edge in the 13th century but strikes many modern people as bizarre. Yet the question it addresses is profound: when Jesus says 'this is my body,' is he speaking metaphorically or making an ontological claim?\n\nThe Eastern Orthodox tradition wisely avoids philosophical definitions. They affirm that the bread and wine become Christ's body and blood by the action of the Holy Spirit (the 'epiclesis' -- the invocation of the Spirit during the liturgy). How this happens is a mystery beyond human categories. The Orthodox critique of transubstantiation is that it over-defines a mystery that should be worshipped, not analyzed.\n\nThe Reformation produced four different eucharistic theologies: Luther insisted on real presence ('is' means 'is'), Zwingli treated it as memorial ('is' means 'represents'), Calvin proposed a middle way (spiritual real presence through the Holy Spirit), and the Anabaptists emphasized the communal meal aspect. These disagreements were not minor -- they split the Protestant movement permanently.",
