        "When you read 'Love your neighbor as yourself,' what does it mean? The answer depends on who you are. A wealthy person reads it differently than a homeless person. A Palestinian Christian reads it differently than an American evangelical. A woman reads it differently than a man. Reader-response hermeneutics takes this seriously: meaning is not just 'in' the text waiting to be extracted -- it is created in the encounter between the text and the reader. Every reading is an interpretation. Every interpreter brings their own experiences, questions, prejudices, and hopes. There is no 'view from nowhere.'",
      intermediate:
        "Reader-response theory emerged in literary studies (Stanley Fish, Wolfgang Iser) and was applied to biblical interpretation by scholars like Fernando Segovia and R.S. Sugirtharajah. The key insight: the historical-critical method claimed to read the Bible 'objectively,' but it was shaped by the social location of its practitioners (overwhelmingly white, male, European, Protestant academics). Their readings reflected their assumptions as surely as anyone else's -- they just had the institutional power to call their reading 'scientific' and everyone else's 'subjective.'\n\nThis does not mean 'anything goes.' Reader-response hermeneutics distinguishes between readings that are responsible to the text (engaging its language, context, and claims seriously) and readings that are irresponsible (ignoring the text to project whatever meaning is convenient). The goal is not to eliminate the reader's perspective but to make it conscious -- to read with awareness of what you bring to the text.\n\nLiberation hermeneutics (reading from the perspective of the poor), feminist hermeneutics (reading with attention to gender), postcolonial hermeneutics (reading against imperial assumptions), and queer hermeneutics (reading with attention to sexuality and gender identity) are all reader-response approaches that have produced genuinely new insights by asking questions the dominant tradition never thought to ask.",
