        "Key Orthodox distinctives that differ from Western Christianity:\n\nTheosis (deification): The goal of the Christian life is not just forgiveness but participation in the divine nature (2 Peter 1:4). Athanasius: 'God became human so that humans might become God.' This does not mean becoming God in essence but sharing in God's energies (grace, love, beauty, life). The entire trajectory of Orthodox spirituality points toward transformation into Christlikeness -- not merely moral improvement but ontological change.\n\nApophatic theology: God is ultimately beyond all human concepts and language. You can say 'God is not finite,' 'God is not material,' 'God is not limited' -- but you cannot finally say what God IS. This keeps theology humble and protects the mystery. Gregory of Nyssa: the closer you get to God, the more you realize how far beyond comprehension God is.\n\nIconography: Icons are not decorations but 'windows into heaven.' The theology of icons (developed through the iconoclastic controversies of the 8th-9th centuries) insists that because God became visible in Christ (the Incarnation), the visible can mediate the invisible. To venerate an icon is not to worship the wood and paint but to honor the reality it represents.\n\nThe Divine Liturgy: Orthodox worship has not fundamentally changed in 1,500 years. The Liturgy of St. John Chrysostom (4th century) is still the standard Sunday service. This continuity is intentional: the liturgy is meant to be participation in the eternal worship of heaven, not a human production updated for contemporary tastes.",
